Despite treatment advances, rheumatoid arthritis (RA) is still associated with 
significant disability, decreased work capacity, and reduced life expectancy. 
Effective immunotherapies to restore immune tolerance promise greater 
specificity, lower toxicity, and a longer-term solution to controlling and 
preventing RA. Design of effective therapies requires a fundamental 
understanding of the critical immunopathogenetic pathways in RA. This article 
reviews advances in the understanding of self-antigen-specific T cells in 
autoimmune diseases including RA and type 1 diabetes, which bring exciting 
insights to the mechanisms underpinning loss of tolerance and how tolerance 
could be restored for disease prevention in the preclinical or recent-onset 
period.

